segments.text: What is the current impact and what will be the future impact of the black women in athletics?
The current impact?
They're good.
They're strong.
They're real good.
I can't understand.
I wish I knew more about physiology because
It's funny that in the United States, I'm talking about track now, the black women are better sprinters, better jumpers, better runners, of course, distance events, they're lacking in that area.
But you can look at my team picture in a minute, and there weren't very many white girls on the team.
They seem to just kind of, they've taken over all the events, and I don't really know why, because you go to
You see the German teams, the Russian teams, who are beating our teams that are all black.
Their teams are all white.
Now, I know drugs enter a little bit there, but I'm not so naive to think that our women are probably not on drugs too, probably not as heavily as they are, and not all the girls.
But I don't understand that.
I think the black women athletes are going to be an incentive to the younger black
And I always tried to pick out, like, Evelyn Ashford is our best American Sprinter.
I would put her poster in the locker room and talk about her and Wilma Rudolph.
And I think that inspires those kids, those younger ones.
With the increased money being spent on women's athletics, do you feel the recruitment of women athletes will become more intense?
I think it will.
I don't think it will ever be.
Well, it may be.
But it will be a while before it's as bad as men's recruiting problems that we have.
knowing some of the coaches that I've known that had to do some recruiting.
It's tough, especially when that money comes in, because those girls will go anywhere.
You know, really easy when there was one school with a little bit of money or everybody was pretty equal.
The problem is you've got major colleges with a lot of money and some minor colleges that have stronger women's programs than what the major college does.
They don't have so much money.
And that's a real problem for them.
That's not real equal.
And so it's going to come down to, it's not right now, but I think it probably will end up who's going to give her most money.
I hear a lot of girls now, it's funny to hear them say, well, maybe I'll get a car, maybe I'll get a business, maybe I'll get some extra money here.
You know, they're thinking, they've seen the men get it, and they think they're going to get it now, you know.
I didn't hear that when I was in school.
Thought never crossed your mind.
But now, I mean, if you're really good, you can hold out for a better deal.
And women are getting to that point.
I hope it doesn't happen, but I think it probably will.
What was your...
reaction of being the first woman inducted into the Texas A&M Hall of Fame?
Do you feel there should be such an institution, Texas A&M?
Yeah, I think it's good to have the Hall of Fame.
I think it's good to have the Walker Student Association.
Everybody kind of has their own area.
I was in shock.
when I got it.
As a matter of fact, I'm on the board of directors of the Letterman's Association, and I know they do that every year, but I never expected it for myself.
And it was almost like I thought, well, maybe I'm not worthy of it to be put up there with the meeting.
I still feel that way.
A lot of people told me I'm stupid for thinking that, because in their eyes, for what I did, it was just as good as what
But it really surprised me, and I wasn't expecting it at all.
But I'm real proud that I was chosen for it, and I'm real proud that I was the first, because I was also the first on the scholarship at A&M for an athletic program.
I was the first female on a full athletic scholarship at A&M, so it kind of went step in step with that.
My first reaction when the guy called me was, are you sure you have the right person?
And he kept saying, well, I think so.
Jackie Sherrill has made major changes concerning women's athletics.
Since firing of Kay Dawn came under scrutiny, do you feel women's athletics at A&M will grow under Jackie Sherrill?
Well, see that, first of all, Kay Dawn and I were married.
And I loved her a lot.
She supported me.
In 1980, she went around to all the Aggie clubs and got them to donate money so that I could travel.
I ran under Texas A&M Track Club.
And my money for my travel was all given to this former Aggies.
She did a lot for me.
I think she did a lot for me while she was here.
My gosh, before she came, we didn't have anything.
And...
I knew when that happened, I don't really know the nitty-gritty of it all, but I know it was really bad.
I like Lynn Hickey over there.
I think she's going to do a good job.
Sometimes I wonder how coaches like Jackie Sherrill, who are athletic directors, also coach and keep their mind equal for all sports.
You know, it may be a better deal if you had someone like Kate Otten who wasn't the basketball coach or the track coach.
Then again, on the other side of the coin, they, if you're a coach, you know what you need, you know, the wants and needs of your athletes, and hopefully you can see that in other sports, too.
I think, I mean, I think you can't help but have the women's programs A&M.
I don't think they were that bad.
I think they were really growing for a while, and they kind of were in a slump, and I think that may be what happened there.
I'm not real sure what Jackie Sherrill's done.
I mean, I got a letter from him, which I thought was real nice, that he took the time to write me a letter, and I'm sure it worked well.
I think if he's the kind of man that I think he is, he's going to want A&M.
He's looking at it for A&M, not
You're going to have to put your things in perspective.
You want A&M to have good programs, not just the men to have good programs, but A&M as a whole.
And athletics should be men's athletics and women's should be athletics and A&M.
And we have both sexes, you know, but quite many opposites.
So I think it's going to grow, and I think it will grow with him because I think he's smart.
He's a smart person, and I think he knows that.
And I think John David Crowe does too.
It was real funny.
Everybody kept apologizing to me at the press conference they called after I had received the award.
And I was really kind of shocked that they were apologizing to me because I felt like they hadn't done enough for me for the accomplishments that I had gotten.
you know, I never really felt that way.
And then after that, I kept apologizing to him.
Then I started thinking, well, you know, if I had been a man, I had a magazine.
Of course, I wasn't a world record holder like Randy Manson.
You know, I think he's, gosh.
See, I still think of myself as not near as good as a man.
I just, it really, I don't, you know, and I don't think I can go in there expecting the same things that Randy did.
It was real funny that they kept apologizing to me.
I kept wondering why they were apologizing to me.
They just kept saying, we hadn't done enough for you.
I just can't believe you did this.
We never recognized you.
We hadn't done enough.
Which kind of makes you, then you go, well, yeah, maybe you guys recognize me enough.
But I never have felt that way.
I think I was dealt a good love, especially since they supported me after I had graduated.
They had given me all the money.
They took a lot of money to send me.
Because all the meets that I competed in were pretty much on the West Coast.
So every pentathlon meet I went to, it was like getting on a plane.
It was like a major trip.
So I feel good.
What do you feel is the future of collegiate women's athletics?
Well, I think they're going to really grow.
I think they're going to start getting some publicity on television, which we're seeing more of now.
More of the nationals being televised.
too fast, and they don't keep rains on it like they're not going to.
Because, well, this year in particular, it'll come as we know about the recruiting process they've had, and it can happen with the women's programs.
So I think that
With the growth rate that we're going to see, parents will be very careful and watch more closely.
And publicity-wise, that will increase, which may also help the professional programs that we're talking about.
It's like you can't start anything in college until you get your high school programs going.
You can't do anything professional until you go to your college programs.
So the one-on-one will prove the other one.
This is the last question.
Do you feel that women's athletics will ever be the same as men's athletics as far as funding?
No.
No, no.
That's what we get for Eve getting Adam to add them.
No, I don't.
I think...
I just don't think it ever will be.
Maybe 50 years from now it might be, but in the very...
near to, you know, 30 years from now type future, I don't think that it will be.
I don't know why.
I think maybe one reason why is the men's programs, football is the biggest moneymaker, and women don't play football.
And they're going to get the most publicity on television, professional, and NCAA.
And even in high school they do.
So men are going to always be caught because of football.
And that's always going to be the biggest sport.
Then you're going to want to win for men.
I don't think they'll ever be equal.
We'll be running close, but I don't think they'll ever be equal.
And we may be equal in certain sports.
But the bigger sports, basketball, women's basketball will never be equal to men's basketball.
Track, they're pretty equal.
I'm going to have to admit they are.
Right now, they're under one coach.
Smaller sports tend to be that way.
Swimming, pretty equal.
You see the Olympic swim meets, NCAA swim meets, usually they're all the same way.
High schools now, in track, they're going, state meets are the same.
They used to be separate.
The girls' state was this weekend, the boys' was this weekend, now they're the same weekend.
So you can see some improvements there, and it'll probably come around now.
Nationals will probably end up being the same weekend, too.
And the Nationals and the NCAA in track will probably be the same weekend.
That's it.
That's it.
